# Appendices
## A MLE Theory

Our PTFA is formulated to provide a probabilistic foundation to PLS. In the body of the paper we propose an iterative procedure to estimate the loadings and data variances associated to our model. In this section we show that a maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) of these quantities reproduces the standard PLS solution. This is akin to the results by Tipping and Bishop (1999) who propose their probabilistic version of PCA and show the same axes of maximal variance are obtained from a MLE of their model. Therefore, our setup also allows us to recover the frequentist properties of estimators for factor loadings and data variances.

Recall from (4) that the distribution of one realization of the data conditional on the factors is Gaussian with mean vector $\boldsymbol{\mu}:=\left[\boldsymbol{f}^{\top} \mathbf{P}^{\top}, \boldsymbol{f}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}^{\top}\right]^{\top}$ and covariance matrix $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}:=$ $\operatorname{diag}\left(\sigma_{x}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{p}, \sigma_{y}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{q}\right)$. Recall we have also stacked the data and loadings into $\mathbf{Z}=[\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{Y}]$ and $\mathbf{L}=\left[\mathbf{P}^{\top}, \mathbf{Q}^{\top}\right]^{\top}$, respectively. Collecting all disturbances $\boldsymbol{e}_{t}:=\left[\boldsymbol{e}_{x, t}^{\top}, \boldsymbol{e}_{y, t}^{\top}\right]$ and stacking into $\mathbf{E}:=\left[e_{1}^{\top}, \ldots, e_{n}^{\top}\right]$, we can express our model equations (2) and (3) succinctly as

$$
\mathbf{Z}=\mathbf{F L}^{\top}+\mathbf{E}
$$

Integrating out the factors according to their $\mathcal{N}\left(0_{k}, \mathbf{V}_{F}\right)$ prior distribution results in the marginal log-likelihood of the data as a function of the loadings, denoted as $\ell(\theta)$. Write $\mathbf{S}:=n^{-1} \mathbf{Z}^{\top} \mathbf{Z}$ for the sample data covariance (the columns of $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}$ are standardized independently) and $\mathbf{C}:=\mathbf{L V}_{F} \mathbf{L}^{\top}+\Sigma$ for the model variance. The log-likelihood can then be expressed as:

$$
\ell(\theta)=-\frac{T}{2}\left[d \log (2 \pi)+\log |\mathbf{C}|+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{C}^{-1} \mathbf{S}\right)\right]
$$

The MLE of $\theta$, denoted as $\widehat{\theta}=(\widehat{\mathbf{P}}, \widehat{\mathbf{Q}}, \widehat{\sigma}_{x}^{2}, \widehat{\sigma}_{y}^{2})$, is therefore given as the solution to

$$
\widehat{\theta}:=\arg \max _{\theta} \ell(\theta)
$$

Note that the assumption of uncorrelated Gaussian errors is made for convenience as it results in a particularly simple likelihood structure. If we assume the factor decomposition to be correctly specified -i.e., that there exists an $\mathbf{L} \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times k}$ such that $\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{Z} \mid \mathbf{F}]=\mathbf{F L}^{\top}$ ) - then, under regularity conditions, our estimator will remain consistent even if the data is subject to other kind of more complex error processes (due to standard quasimaximum likelihood results; see for example Gong and Samaniego, 1981; Gourieroux et al., 1984).

While we use the maximum likelihood moniker following earlier work by Tipping and Bishop (1999), $\widehat{\theta}$ is technically a maximum a-posteriori (MAP) estimator as it can depend on the assumed factor prior variance $\mathbf{V}_{F}$. For the remainder of the derivation and to

economize on notation we set $\mathbf{V}_{F}=\mathbf{I}_{k}$, as it also results in the canonical PLS formulation (for more details, see Frank and Friedman, 1993; Hastie et al., 2001).

The parameters $\theta$ enter the likelihood only through the value of $\mathbf{C}$, with a gradient equal to

$$
\frac{\partial \ell(\theta)}{\partial \mathbf{C}}=-\frac{n}{2}\left(\mathbf{C}^{-1}-\mathbf{C}^{-1} \mathbf{S C}^{-1}\right)
$$

Writing $\overline{\mathbf{L}}=\left[\overline{\mathbf{P}}^{\top}, \overline{\mathbf{Q}}^{\top}\right]^{\top}, \overline{\mathbf{\Sigma}}:=\operatorname{diag}\left(\widehat{\sigma}_{x}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{p}, \widehat{\sigma}_{y}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{q}\right)$, and $\overline{\mathbf{C}}:=\overline{\mathbf{L}} \overline{\mathbf{L}}^{\top}+\overline{\mathbf{\Sigma}}$, this means that the maximum likelihood solutions for the loadings $\mathbf{L}$ are characterized by

$$
\mathbf{0}_{d \times k}=\left[\frac{\partial \ell(\hat{\theta})}{\partial \mathbf{C}}\right]^{\top} \frac{\partial \ell(\hat{\theta})}{\partial \mathbf{L}} \Longrightarrow\left(\mathbf{S} \overline{\mathbf{C}}^{-1}-\mathbf{I}_{d}\right)\left[\frac{\overline{\mathbf{P}}}{\overline{\mathbf{Q}}}\right]=\mathbf{0}_{d \times k}
$$

The first-order condition (A.5) exhibits the same three classes of solutions as explored by Tipping and Bishop (1999), plus an additional interesting special case. First, the trivial solution sets $\overline{\mathbf{L}}=\mathbf{0}_{d \times k}$, which represents a minimum of the log-likelihood $\ell(\theta)$. Second, we obtain a solution if we assume our implied model variance to equal the data variance, such that $\overline{\mathbf{C}}=\mathbf{S}$. Letting $\mathbf{S}_{X}, \mathbf{S}_{Y}$ and $\mathbf{S}_{X Y}$ denote the blocks of $\mathbf{S}$ partitioned according to features and targets, we can then identify the components $\overline{\mathbf{P}}$ and $\overline{\mathbf{Q}}$ from the set of equations given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\overline{\mathbf{P}} \overline{\mathbf{P}}^{\top} & =\mathbf{S}_{X}-\widehat{\sigma}_{x}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{p} \\
\overline{\mathbf{Q}} \overline{\mathbf{Q}}^{\top} & =\mathbf{S}_{Y}-\widehat{\sigma}_{y}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{q} \\
\overline{\mathbf{P}} \overline{\mathbf{Q}}^{\top} & =\mathbf{S}_{X Y}
\end{aligned}
$$

Note that equations (A.6) require the last $p-k$ eigenvalues of $\mathbf{S}_{X}$ to be equal to each other, and similarly for the last $q-k$ eigenvalues of $\mathbf{S}_{Y}$. In this case, $\overline{\mathbf{P}}$ is constructed from the eigenvectors of $\mathbf{S}_{X}, \overline{\mathbf{Q}}$ from the eigenvectors of $\mathbf{S}_{Y}$, and the components are rotated to ensure $\overline{\mathbf{P}} \overline{\mathbf{Q}}^{\top}=\mathbf{S}_{X Y}$.
An explicit construction for the solutions in this case can be provided as follows. Let $\mathbf{X}_{k}:=\mathbf{U}_{X} \mathbf{D}_{X} \mathbf{V}_{X}^{\top}$ and $\mathbf{Y}_{k}:=\mathbf{U}_{Y} \mathbf{D}_{Y} \mathbf{V}_{Y}^{\top}$ be the best rank $k$ approximations to the data matrices $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}$, respectively. Therefore, $\mathbf{U}_{X}$ and $\mathbf{U}_{Y}$ are $T \times k$ matrices with orthogonal columns containing the left singular vectors, $\mathbf{V}_{X}$ and $\mathbf{V}_{Y}$ are $k \times k$ orthogonal matrices containing the right singular vectors, and $\mathbf{D}_{X}$ and $\mathbf{D}_{Y}$ are $k \times k$ diagonal matrices holding the largest $k$ singular values for features $\mathbf{X}$ and targets $\mathbf{Y}$, respectively. One can then check the following solutions satisfy (A.6):

$$
\begin{aligned}
\overline{\mathbf{P}} & =\mathbf{V}_{X}\left(\frac{1}{T} \mathbf{D}_{X}^{2}-\widehat{\sigma}_{x}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{k}\right)^{1 / 2} \mathbf{V}_{P}^{\top} \\
\overline{\mathbf{Q}} & =\mathbf{V}_{Y}\left(\frac{1}{T} \mathbf{D}_{Y}^{2}-\widehat{\sigma}_{y}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{k}\right)^{1 / 2} \mathbf{V}_{Q}^{\top} \\
\mathbf{V}_{P} & =\mathbf{V}_{Q}\left(\mathbf{D}_{Y}^{2}-T \cdot \widehat{\sigma}_{y}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{k}\right)^{-1 / 2} \mathbf{D}_{Y} \mathbf{U}_{Y}^{\top} \mathbf{U}_{X} \mathbf{D}_{X}\left(\mathbf{D}_{X}^{2}-T \cdot \widehat{\sigma}_{x}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{k}\right)^{-1 / 2}
\end{aligned}
$$

This solution leaves $\mathbf{V}_{Q}$ as an arbitrary $k \times k$ orthogonal matrix, and sets $\widetilde{\sigma}_{x}^{2}$ equal to the smallest eigenvalue of $\mathbf{S}_{X}$ and $\widetilde{\sigma}_{g}^{2}$ equal to the smallest eigenvalue of $\mathbf{S}_{Y}$ (recall the trailing eigenvalues after the $k$-th one are assumed equal for both $\mathbf{S}_{X}$ and $\mathbf{S}_{X}$ ). Note that this solution corresponds to extracting factors for $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}$ independently using PCA, and then rotating the principal axes of the feature loadings according to the weighted covariance $\mathbf{S}_{X Y}$ between features and targets.
The third class of solutions represents the most interesting case likely to be encountered in practice, where (A.5) is satisfied but $\widetilde{\mathbf{C}} \neq \mathbf{S}$ so that our covariance model is misspecified. That is, we recognize that the isotropic Gaussian error terms in (2)-(3) are not to be taken as true modeling choices for the features nor targets, and are rather used as a working assumption to obtain a framework for probabilistic targeted factor recovery.
Define the marginal covariance matrices implied from the model as $\widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}:=\widetilde{\mathbf{P}} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}}^{\top}+\widetilde{\sigma}_{x}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{p}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{Y}:=\widetilde{\mathbf{Q}} \widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}^{\top}+\widetilde{\sigma}_{g}^{2} \mathbf{I}_{q}$. Additionally, define the conditional covariance of $\mathbf{Y}$ given $\mathbf{X}$ implied from the model as $\widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{Y \mid X}:=\widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{Y}-\widetilde{\mathbf{Q}} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}} \widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}^{\top}$. Using these definitions, the system of equations (A.5) can be expressed as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(\mathbf{S}_{X} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1}-\mathbf{I}_{p}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{P}}+\frac{1}{T} \mathbf{X}^{\top}\left(\mathbf{Y}-\mathbf{X} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}} \widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}^{\top}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{Y \mid X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}\left(\mathbf{I}_{k}-\widetilde{\mathbf{P}}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}}\right)=\mathbf{0}_{p \times k} \\
& \left(\mathbf{S}_{X Y}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}}-\widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}\right)+\frac{1}{T} \mathbf{Y}^{\top}\left(\mathbf{Y}-\mathbf{X} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}} \widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}^{\top}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{Y \mid X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}\left(\mathbf{I}_{k}-\widetilde{\mathbf{P}}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}}\right)=\mathbf{0}_{q \times k}
\end{aligned}
$$

This representation of the first-order conditions showcases that the loadings can be obtained as the solution to the simpler system

$$
\begin{aligned}
\widetilde{\mathbf{P}} & =\mathbf{S}_{X} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}} \\
\widetilde{\mathbf{Q}} & =\mathbf{S}_{X Y}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}} \\
\mathbf{Y} & =\mathbf{X} \widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X}^{-1} \widetilde{\mathbf{P}} \widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}^{\top}
\end{aligned}
$$

Equations (A.9) and (A.10) jointly imply that the columns of $\widetilde{\mathbf{P}}$ take into account information from the eigenvectors of the feature variance $\mathbf{S}_{X}$ and covariance matrix $\mathbf{S}_{X Y}$. Finally, equation (A.11) provides the explicit decomposition satisfied by the estimated loadings $\widetilde{\mathbf{P}}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}$. This is precisely the prediction produced by the canonical PLS setting with multiple targets. These results showcase that our PTFA framework indeed provides a probabilistic foundation for standard PLS as it reproduces the spirit of the non-random solution from the NIPALS algorithm.

Finally, we note one more special case of interest that does not have an analogue to the PPCA framework in Tipping and Bishop (1999). Specifically, this occurs when one is interested in targeted recovery of factors for a set of response variables with a smaller number of variables than the suspected number of components, such that $q<k$. In this case, as the column space of $\mathbf{Y}$ can be spanned by linear combinations of the $k$ scores without loss of generality (as long as they are orthogonal), we can directly assume $\widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{Y}=$ $\mathbf{S}_{Y}$. In this case, loadings $\widetilde{\mathbf{Q}}$ can be assumed orthogonal and can be recovered using PCA. However, we should still allow for $\widetilde{\mathbf{C}}_{X} \neq \mathbf{S}_{X}$. In this case, the solution is a hybrid solution between (A.7) and (A.9)-(A.11).

# B EM Derivation 

We let $\bar{\theta}$ represent an initial or current fixed value of the parameters. The expectation (E) step requires us to obtain the observed-data likelihood by integrating out the factors according to their posterior distribution. This results in the objective function:

$$
Q(\theta \mid \bar{\theta})=\mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{F} \mid \mathbf{X}, \mathbf{Y} ; \bar{\theta}}[\log p(\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{Y}, \mathbf{F} \mid \theta)]
$$

Our framework allows us to produce a closed-form solution for the E-step. The maximization (M) step, then consists in optimizing $Q(\cdot)$ with respect to the variables and parameters with a view of deriving updating rules. These updating rules are derived using the following steps:

1. To update $\mathbf{P}$, we maximize the expected log-likelihood term involving $\mathbf{X}$

$$
Q_{X}(\mathbf{P}):=\mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{F} \mid \mathbf{X}, \mathbf{Y} ; \bar{\theta}}\left[-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{X}^{2}}\left\|\mathbf{X}-\mathbf{F P}^{\top}\right\|_{F}^{2}\right]
$$

expanding the norm and taking expectations we get

$$
Q_{X}(\mathbf{P})=-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{X}^{2}} \mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{F} \mid \mathbf{X}, \mathbf{Y} ; \bar{\theta}}\left[\operatorname{Tr}\left(\left(\mathbf{X}-\mathbf{F P}^{\top}\right)^{\top}\left(\mathbf{X}-\mathbf{F P}^{\top}\right)\right)\right]
$$

This simplifies to:

$$
Q_{X}(\mathbf{P})=-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{X}^{2}}\left[\|\mathbf{X}\|_{F}^{2}-2 \operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbf{M P}^{\top}\right)+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P V P}^{\top}\right)\right]
$$

Maximizing this quadratic form in $\mathbf{P}$ gives the first-order condition $\mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbf{M}=\mathbf{P V}$, which can be solved to yield:

$$
\mathbf{P}=\mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbf{M V}^{-1}
$$

2. To update $\mathbf{Q}$, we maximize the expected log-likelihood term involving $\mathbf{Y}$ :

$$
Q_{Y}(\mathbf{Q}):=\mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{F} \mid \mathbf{X}, \mathbf{Y} ; \bar{\theta}}\left[-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{y}^{2}}\left\|\mathbf{Y}-\mathbf{F Q}^{\top}\right\|_{F}^{2}\right]
$$

Expanding and simplifying, we obtain an expression similar to before:

$$
Q_{Y}(\mathbf{Q})=-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{y}^{2}}\left[\|\mathbf{Y}\|_{F}^{2}-2 \operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{Y}^{\top} \mathbf{M Q}^{\top}\right)+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{Q V Q}^{\top}\right)\right]
$$

Maximizing this quadratic form in $\mathbf{Q}$ gives the first-order condition $\mathbf{Y}^{\top} \mathbf{M}=\mathbf{Q V}$, which can be solved to yield:

$$
\mathbf{Q}=\mathbf{Y}^{\top} \mathbf{M V}^{-1}
$$

3. To update $\sigma_{x}^{2}$, We only need the term involving $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
Q\left(\sigma_{x}^{2}\right) & =-\frac{T p}{2} \log \left(\sigma_{x}^{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{x}^{2}} \mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{F} \mid \mathbf{X}, \mathbf{Y}, \vec{B}}\left[\left\|\mathbf{X}-\mathbf{F P}^{\top}\right\|_{F}^{2}\right] \\
& =-\frac{T p}{2} \log \left(\sigma_{x}^{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{x}^{2}}\left[\|\mathbf{X}\|_{F}^{2}-2 \operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbf{M P}^{\top}\right)+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P V P}^{\top}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

To maximize $Q\left(\sigma_{x}^{2}\right)$ with respect to $\sigma_{x}^{2}$, take the derivative and set it to zero:

$$
\frac{\partial Q\left(\sigma_{x}^{2}\right)}{\partial \sigma_{x}^{2}}=-\frac{T p}{2 \sigma_{x}^{2}}+\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{x}^{4}}\left[\|\mathbf{X}\|_{F}^{2}-2 \operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbf{M P}^{\top}\right)+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P V P}^{\top}\right)\right]=0
$$

Solving for $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ :

$$
\sigma_{x}^{2}=\frac{1}{T p}\left[\|\mathbf{X}\|_{F}^{2}-2 \operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbf{M P}^{\top}\right)+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P V P}^{\top}\right)\right]
$$

Using the first-order condition satisfied by $\mathbf{P}$ and combining the terms in the previous expression, our estimate can be succinctly computed as:

$$
\sigma_{x}^{2}=\frac{1}{T p}\left[\|\mathbf{X}\|_{F}^{2}-\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P}^{\top} \mathbf{P V}\right)\right]
$$

4. To update $\sigma_{y}^{2}$, similar calculations can be performed as in the last step to find:

$$
\sigma_{y}^{2}=\frac{1}{T q}\left[\|\mathbf{Y}\|_{F}^{2}-\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{Q}^{\top} \mathbf{Q V}\right)\right]
$$

# C Algorithms 

Algorithm 1 EM Algorithm for Probabilistic Targeted Factor Extraction
Require: Predictor matrix $\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times p}$, target matrix $\mathbf{Y} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times q}$, number of components $k$, starting values $\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \sigma_{x, 0}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}\right)$, prior variance $\mathbf{V}_{F}$, tolerance $\epsilon$, maximum iterations $S$
1: Center and scale the Data:

$$
\mathbf{X} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{X}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{x}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{x}\right)^{-1}, \quad \mathbf{Y} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{Y}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{y}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{y}\right)^{-1}
$$

where for the columns of $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}, \boldsymbol{m}_{x}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{x}_{t}$ and $\boldsymbol{m}_{y}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{y}_{t}$ are the vector of means, whereas $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the vectors of standard deviations, respectively.
2: repeat
3: E-step: Expectation
4: $\quad$ Collect all initial parameters into $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \sigma_{x, 0}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}\right)$
5: $\quad$ Compute Posterior Covariance $(\boldsymbol{\Omega})$ :

$$
\boldsymbol{\Omega} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{V}_{F}^{-1}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{P}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{Q}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{0}\right)^{-1}
$$

6: $\quad$ Compute Posterior Mean $(\mathbf{M})$ :

$$
\mathbf{M} \leftarrow\left(\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{X} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{Y} \mathbf{Q}_{0}\right) \boldsymbol{\Omega}
$$

7: M-step: Maximization
8: $\quad \mathbf{V} \leftarrow T \cdot \Omega+\mathbf{M}^{\top} \mathbf{M}$
9: Update $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ jointly as:

$$
\left[\begin{array}{l}
\mathbf{P}_{1} \\
\mathbf{Q}_{1}
\end{array}\right] \leftarrow\left[\begin{array}{l}
\mathbf{X}^{\top} \\
\mathbf{Y}^{\top}
\end{array}\right] \mathbf{M V}^{-1}
$$

10: $\quad$ Update $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ :

$$
\sigma_{x, 1}^{2} \leftarrow \frac{1}{T p}\left[\|\mathbf{X}\|_{F}^{2}-\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{1} \mathbf{V}\right)\right]
$$

11: $\quad$ Update $\sigma_{y}^{2}$ :

$$
\sigma_{y, 1}^{2} \leftarrow \frac{1}{T q}\left[\|\mathbf{Y}\|_{F}^{2}-\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{Q}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{1} \mathbf{V}\right)\right]
$$

12: Collect updated parameters as $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}, \mathbf{Q}_{1}, \sigma_{x, 1}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 1}^{2}\right)$
13: until convergence $\left\|\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0}\right\|<\epsilon$ or $S$ iterations are reached
14: return Loading matrices $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times k}$ and $\mathbf{Q} \in \mathbb{R}^{q \times k}$, as well as noise variances $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ and $\sigma_{y}^{2}$ from final estimate $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}$

Algorithm 2 EM Algorithm for Probabilistic Targeted Factor Extraction with Missing-atRandom Data
Require: Predictor matrix $\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times p}$, target matrix $\mathbf{Y} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times q}$, number of components $k$, starting values $\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \sigma_{x, 0}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}\right)$, prior variance $\mathbf{V}_{F}$, tolerance $\epsilon$, maximum iterations $S$
1: Missing value indices: let $\tau_{t, j}^{(X)}=1$ if entry $i, j$ of matrix $\mathbf{X}$ is missing, 0 otherwise. Define $\tau_{t, j}^{(Y)}$ similarly for $\mathbf{Y}$
2: Initial imputation step: Replace $\mathbf{X}_{t, j} \leftarrow 0$ and $\mathbf{Y}_{t, j} \leftarrow 0$ if $\tau_{t, j}^{(X)}=1$ and $\tau_{t, j}^{(Y)}=1$, respectively
3: Center and scale the Data:

$$
\mathbf{X} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{X}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{x}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{x}\right)^{-1}, \quad \mathbf{Y} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{Y}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{y}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{y}\right)^{-1}
$$

where for the columns of $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}, \boldsymbol{m}_{x}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{x}_{t}$ and $\boldsymbol{m}_{y}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{y}_{t}$ are the vector of means, whereas $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the vectors of standard deviations, respectively.
4: repeat
5: E-step: Expectation
6: Collect all initial parameters into $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \sigma_{x, 0}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}\right)$
7: Compute Posterior Covariance $(\boldsymbol{\Omega})$ :

$$
\boldsymbol{\Omega} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{V}_{F}^{-1}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{P}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{Q}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{0}\right)^{-1}
$$

8: Compute Posterior Mean (M):

$$
\mathbf{M} \leftarrow\left(\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{X} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{Y} \mathbf{Q}_{0}\right) \boldsymbol{\Omega}
$$

9: M-step: Maximization
10: $\quad \mathbf{V} \leftarrow T \cdot \boldsymbol{\Omega}+\mathbf{M}^{\top} \mathbf{M}$
11: Update the missing value entries with the latest EM fit:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbf{X}_{t, j} \leftarrow \sum_{c=1}^{k} \mathbf{M}_{i c} \mathbf{P}_{j c} \quad \text { if } \quad \tau_{t, j}^{(X)}=1 \\
& \mathbf{Y}_{t, j} \leftarrow \sum_{c=1}^{k} \mathbf{M}_{i c} \mathbf{Q}_{j c} \quad \text { if } \quad \tau_{t, j}^{(Y)}=1
\end{aligned}
$$

12: Update $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ jointly as:

$$
\left[\begin{array}{l}
\mathbf{P}_{1} \\
\mathbf{Q}_{1}
\end{array}\right] \leftarrow\left[\begin{array}{l}
\mathbf{X}^{\top} \\
\mathbf{Y}^{\top}
\end{array}\right] \mathbf{M V}^{-1}
$$

13: Update $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ :

$$
\sigma_{x, 1}^{2} \leftarrow \frac{1}{T p}\left[\|\mathbf{X}\|_{F}^{2}-\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{1} \mathbf{V}\right)\right]
$$

14: $\quad$ Update $\sigma_{y}^{2}$ :

$$
\sigma_{y, 1}^{2} \leftarrow \frac{1}{T q}\left[\|\mathbf{Y}\|_{F}^{2}-\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{Q}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{1} \mathbf{V}\right)\right]
$$

15: Collect updated parameters as $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}, \mathbf{Q}_{1}, \sigma_{x, 1}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 1}^{2}\right)$
16: until convergence $\left\|\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0}\right\|<\epsilon$ or $S$ iterations are reached
17: return Loading matrices $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times k}$ and $\mathbf{Q} \in \mathbb{R}^{q \times k}$, as well as noise variances $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ and $\sigma_{y}^{2}$ from final estimate $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}$

# Algorithm 3 EM Algorithm for Probabilistic PLS with Mixed-Frequency Data 

Require: High-frequency predictor matrix $\widetilde{\mathbf{X}} \in \mathbb{R}^{(T L) \times p}$, low-frequency target matrix $\mathbf{Y} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times q}$, low-to-high-frequency period $L$, number of components $k$, starting values $\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \sigma_{x, 0}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}\right)$, prior variance $\mathbf{V}_{F}$, tolerance $\epsilon$, maximum iterations $S$
1: Reshape $\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}$ into a $T \times(p L)$ matrix $\mathbf{X}$ :

$$
\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{x}_{1}^{\top} \\
\vdots \\
\boldsymbol{x}_{L}^{\top} \\
\vdots \\
\boldsymbol{x}_{(T-1) L+1}^{\top} \\
\vdots \\
\boldsymbol{x}_{T L}^{\top}
\end{array}\right] \mapsto\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\boldsymbol{x}_{1}^{\top} & \cdots & \boldsymbol{x}_{L}^{\top} \\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
\boldsymbol{x}_{(T-1) L+1}^{\top} & \cdots & \boldsymbol{x}_{T L}^{\top}
\end{array}\right]=\mathbf{X}
$$

2: Center and scale the Data:

$$
\mathbf{X} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{X}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{x}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(s_{x}\right)^{-1}, \quad \mathbf{Y} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{Y}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{y}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(s_{y}\right)^{-1}
$$

where for the columns of $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}, \boldsymbol{m}_{x}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{x}_{t}$ and $\boldsymbol{m}_{y}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{y}_{t}$ are the vector of means, whereas $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the vectors of standard deviations, respectively.
3: repeat
4: E-step: Expectation
5: Collect all initial parameters into $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \sigma_{x, 0}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}\right)$
6: $\quad$ Compute Posterior Covariance $(\boldsymbol{\Omega})$ :

$$
\boldsymbol{\Omega} \leftarrow\left[\mathbf{I}_{L} \otimes\left(\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{P}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\mathbf{V}_{F}^{-1}\right)+\frac{1}{L \cdot \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{1}_{L \times L} \otimes\left(\mathbf{Q}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{0}\right)\right]^{-1}
$$

7: Compute Posterior Mean (M):

$$
\mathbf{M} \leftarrow\left[\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{X}^{(1)} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{Y} \mathbf{Q}_{0} \cdots \frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{X}^{(L)} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{Y} \mathbf{Q}_{0}\right] \boldsymbol{\Omega}
$$

8: M-step: Maximization
9: $\quad \mathbf{V}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}\mathbf{V}_{1,1} & \cdots & \mathbf{V}_{1, L} \\ \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ \mathbf{V}_{L, 1} & \cdots & \mathbf{V}_{L, L}\end{array}\right] \leftarrow T \cdot \boldsymbol{\Omega}+\mathbf{M}^{\top} \mathbf{M}$
10: Update $\mathbf{P}$ as:

$$
\mathbf{P}_{1} \leftarrow\left(\sum_{\ell=1}^{L} \mathbf{X}^{(\ell) \top} \mathbf{M}^{(\ell)}\right)\left(\sum_{\ell=1}^{L} \mathbf{V}_{\ell, \ell}\right)^{-1}
$$

11: Update $\mathbf{Q}$ as:

$$
\mathbf{Q}_{1} \leftarrow L \cdot\left(\mathbf{Y}^{\top} \sum_{\ell=1}^{L} \mathbf{M}^{(\ell)}\right)\left(\sum_{r=1}^{L} \sum_{\ell=1}^{L} \mathbf{V}_{\ell, r}\right)^{-1}
$$

12: $\quad$ Update $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ :

$$
\sigma_{x, 1}^{2} \leftarrow \frac{1}{T L p}\left\{\|\mathbf{X}\|_{F}^{2}-\operatorname{Tr}\left[\mathbf{P}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{1}\left(\sum_{\ell=1}^{L} \mathbf{V}_{\ell, \ell}\right)\right]\right\}
$$

13: $\quad$ Update $\sigma_{y}^{2}$ :

$$
\sigma_{y, 1}^{2} \leftarrow \frac{L}{T q} \operatorname{Tr}\left\{\mathbf{Y}^{\top}\left[\mathbf{Y}-\frac{1}{L}\left(\sum_{\ell=1}^{L} \mathbf{M}^{(\ell)}\right) \mathbf{Q}_{1}^{\top}\right]\right\}
$$

14: Collect updated parameters as $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}, \mathbf{Q}_{1}, \sigma_{x, 1}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 1}^{2}\right)$
15: until convergence $\left\|\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0}\right\|<\varepsilon$ or $S$ iterations are reached
16: return Loading matrices $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times k}$ and $\mathbf{Q} \in \mathbb{R}^{q \times k}$, as well as noise variances $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ and $\sigma_{y}^{2}$ from final estimate $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}$

Algorithm 4 EM Algorithm for Probabilistic PLS with Exponential Weighted Moving Average (EWMA) Stochastic Volatility
Require: Predictor matrix $\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times p}$, target matrix $\mathbf{Y} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times q}$, number of components $k$, starting values $\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \tilde{\sigma}_{x}^{2}, \tilde{\sigma}_{y}^{2}\right)$, prior variance $\mathbf{V}_{F}$, EWMA smoothing parameters $\left(\lambda_{x}, \lambda_{y}\right)$, tolerance $\epsilon$, maximum iterations $S$
1: Center and scale the Data:

$$
\mathbf{X} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{X}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{x}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{x}\right)^{-1}, \quad \mathbf{Y} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{Y}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{y}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{y}\right)^{-1}
$$

where for the columns of $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}, \boldsymbol{m}_{x}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{x}_{t}$ and $\boldsymbol{m}_{y}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{y}_{t}$ are the vector of means, whereas $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the vectors of standard deviations, respectively.
2: Start the $T$-dimensional stochastic volatility vectors $\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}$ and $\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}$ as constant:

$$
\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}(t) \leftarrow \tilde{\sigma}_{x}^{2} \quad \text { and } \quad \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}(t) \leftarrow \tilde{\sigma}_{y}^{2} \quad \text { for all } \quad t=1, \ldots, T
$$

3: repeat
4: E-step: Expectation
5: Collect initial parameters into $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \boldsymbol{\sigma}_{x, 0}^{2}, \boldsymbol{\sigma}_{y, 0}^{2}\right)$
6: for $t=1, \ldots, T$ do
7: $\quad$ Compute and store posterior covariance per period $\left(\boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t}\right)$ :

$$
\boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{V}_{F}^{-1}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}(t)} \mathbf{P}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}(t)} \mathbf{Q}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{0}\right)^{-1}
$$

8: $\quad$ Compute posterior mean per period $\left(\boldsymbol{m}_{t}\right)$ :

$$
\boldsymbol{m}_{t} \leftarrow \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t}\left(\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}(t)} \mathbf{P}_{0}^{\top} \boldsymbol{x}_{t}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}(t)} \mathbf{Q}_{0}^{\top} \boldsymbol{y}_{t}\right)
$$

9: end for
10: Stack posterior means into $T \times k$ matrix:

$$
\mathbf{M} \leftarrow\left[\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{m}_{1}^{\top} \\
\vdots \\
\boldsymbol{m}_{T}^{\top}
\end{array}\right]
$$

11: M-step: Maximization
12: $\quad \mathbf{V} \leftarrow \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t}+\mathbf{M}^{\top} \mathbf{M}$

13: Update $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ jointly as:

$$
\left[\begin{array}{l}
\mathbf{P}_{1} \\
\mathbf{Q}_{1}
\end{array}\right] \leftarrow\left[\begin{array}{l}
\mathbf{X}^{\top} \\
\mathbf{Y}^{\top}
\end{array}\right] \mathbf{M V}^{-1}
$$

14: Compute Residuals:

$$
\widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{x}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_{x, 1}^{\top} \\
\vdots \\
\widehat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_{x, T}^{\top}
\end{array}\right] \leftarrow \mathbf{X}-\mathbf{M P}_{1}^{\top} \quad \text { and } \quad \widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{y}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_{y, 1}^{\top} \\
\vdots \\
\widehat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_{y, T}^{\top}
\end{array}\right] \leftarrow \mathbf{Y}-\mathbf{M Q}_{1}^{\top}
$$

15: Update first-period stochastic volatility estimates:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sigma_{x, 1}^{2}(1) \leftarrow \frac{1}{p}\left[\left\|\widehat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_{x, 1}\right\|_{2}^{2}+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{1} \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{1}\right)\right] \\
& \sigma_{y, 1}^{2}(1) \leftarrow \frac{1}{q}\left[\left\|\widehat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_{y, 1}\right\|_{2}^{2}+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{Q}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{1} \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{1}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

16: Update remaining stochastic volatility estimates in $\sigma_{x, 1}^{2}$ and $\sigma_{y, 1}^{2}$ using EWMA:

17: for $t=2, \ldots, T$ do

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sigma_{x, 1}^{2}(t) \leftarrow \lambda_{x} \cdot \sigma_{x, 1}^{2}(t-1)+\left(1-\lambda_{x}\right) \cdot \frac{1}{p}\left[\left\|\widehat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_{x, t}\right\|_{2}^{2}+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{1} \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t}\right)\right] \\
& \sigma_{y, 1}^{2}(t) \leftarrow \lambda_{y} \cdot \sigma_{y, 1}^{2}(t-1)+\left(1-\lambda_{y}\right) \cdot \frac{1}{q}\left[\left\|\widehat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_{y, t}\right\|_{2}^{2}+\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{Q}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{1} \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

18: end for
19: Collect updated parameters into $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}, \mathbf{Q}_{1}, \sigma_{x, 1}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 1}^{2}\right)$
20: until convergence $\left\|\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0}\right\|<\epsilon$ or $S$ iterations are reached
21: return Loading matrices $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times k}$ and $\mathbf{Q} \in \mathbb{R}^{q \times k}$, as well as time-varying noise variances $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ and $\sigma_{y}^{2}$ from final estimates $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}$

Algorithm 5 EM Algorithm for Probabilistic Targeted Factor Extraction with Factor Dynamics
Require: Predictor matrix $\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times p}$, target matrix $\mathbf{Y} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times q}$, number of components $k$, starting values $\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \sigma_{x, 0}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}, \mathbf{A}_{0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{v, 0}, \boldsymbol{f}_{0}\right)$, tolerance $\epsilon$, maximum iterations $S$
1: Center and scale the Data:

$$
\mathbf{X} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{X}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{x}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{x}\right)^{-1}, \quad \mathbf{Y} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{Y}-\mathbf{1}_{T} \boldsymbol{m}_{y}^{\top}\right) \operatorname{diag}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{y}\right)^{-1}
$$

where for the columns of $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}, \boldsymbol{m}_{x}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{x}_{t}$ and $\boldsymbol{m}_{y}:=(1 / T) \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{y}_{t}$ are the vector of means, whereas $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the vectors of standard deviations, respectively.
2: repeat
3: E-step: Expectation
4: Collect all initial parameters into $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{0}, \mathbf{Q}_{0}, \sigma_{x, 0}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 0}^{2}, \mathbf{A}_{0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{v, 0}, \boldsymbol{f}_{0}\right)$
5: $\quad$ Store matrix $\mathbf{H}_{A}$ as a block-banded matrix:

$$
\mathbf{H}_{A} \leftarrow\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\mathbf{I}_{k} & & & \\
-\mathbf{A}_{0} & \mathbf{I}_{k} & & \\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \\
\mathbf{0}_{k \times k} & \mathbf{0}_{k \times k} & \cdots & \mathbf{I}_{k} \\
\mathbf{0}_{k \times k} & \mathbf{0}_{k \times k} & \cdots & -\mathbf{A}_{0} & \mathbf{I}_{k}
\end{array}\right]
$$

6: Pre-compute vectorized prior mean $\operatorname{vec}\left(\mathbf{M}_{0}^{\top}\right):=\mathbf{H}_{A} \boldsymbol{\mu}_{0}$ :

$$
\operatorname{vec}\left(\mathbf{M}_{0}^{\top}\right) \leftarrow\left[\begin{array}{c}
\mathbf{A}_{0} \boldsymbol{f}_{0} \\
\mathbf{0}_{k} \\
\vdots \\
\mathbf{0}_{k}
\end{array}\right]=\mathbf{H}_{A} \boldsymbol{\mu}_{0}
$$

7: Compute posterior precision $\left(\boldsymbol{\Omega}^{-1}\right)$ and store as banded matrix:

$$
\boldsymbol{\Omega}^{-1} \leftarrow \mathbf{H}_{A}^{\top}\left(\mathbf{I}_{T} \otimes \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{v, 0}^{-1}\right) \mathbf{H}_{A}+I_{T} \otimes\left(\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{P}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{Q}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{0}\right)
$$

8: Compute vectorized posterior mean $(\mathbf{M})$ using a banded matrix system solver:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \operatorname{vec}\left(\mathbf{M}^{\top}\right) \leftarrow \boldsymbol{\Omega}\left\{\mathbf{H}_{A}^{\top}\left(\mathbf{I}_{T} \otimes \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{v, 0}^{-1}\right) \operatorname{vec}\right. & \left.\left(\mathbf{M}_{0}^{\top}\right) \\
& \left.+\left[I_{T} \otimes\left(\frac{1}{\sigma_{x, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{X} \mathbf{P}_{0}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{y, 0}^{2}} \mathbf{Y} \mathbf{Q}_{0}\right)\right] \operatorname{vec}\left(\mathbf{Z}^{\top}\right)\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

9: M-step: Maximization
10: Compute only the following quantities from the banded Cholesky decomposition of the posterior covariance matrix:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbf{V}_{0} \leftarrow \sum_{t=1}^{T} \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t, t}+m_{t} m_{t}^{\top} \\
& \mathbf{V}_{1} \leftarrow \sum_{t=2}^{T} \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t-1, t-1}+m_{t-1} m_{t-1}^{\top} \\
& \mathbf{V}_{10} \leftarrow \sum_{t=2}^{T} \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t-1, t}+m_{t-1} m_{t}^{\top} \\
& \mathbf{V}_{20} \leftarrow \sum_{t=3}^{T} \boldsymbol{\Omega}_{t-2, t}+m_{t-2} m_{t}^{\top}
\end{aligned}
$$

11: Update $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ jointly as:

$$
\left[\begin{array}{l}
\mathbf{P}_{1} \\
\mathbf{Q}_{1}
\end{array}\right] \leftarrow\left[\begin{array}{l}
\mathbf{X}^{\top} \\
\mathbf{Y}^{\top}
\end{array}\right] \mathbf{M V}_{0}^{-1}
$$

12: Update $\sigma_{x}^{2}$ :

$$
\sigma_{x, 1}^{2} \leftarrow \frac{1}{T p}\left[\|\mathbf{X}\|_{F}^{2}-\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{1} \mathbf{V}_{0}\right)\right]
$$

13: $\quad$ Update $\sigma_{y}^{2}$ :

$$
\sigma_{y, 1}^{2} \leftarrow \frac{1}{T q}\left[\|\mathbf{Y}\|_{F}^{2}-\operatorname{Tr}\left(\mathbf{Q}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{Q}_{1} \mathbf{V}_{0}\right)\right]
$$

14: $\quad$ Update $\mathbf{A}$ :

$$
\mathbf{A}_{1} \leftarrow \mathbf{V}_{20}^{-1} \mathbf{V}_{10}
$$

15: $\quad$ Update $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{v}$ :

$$
\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{v, 1} \leftarrow \operatorname{diag}\left[\mathbf{V}_{0}+\left(m_{1}-\mathbf{A}_{1} f_{0}\right)\left(m_{1}-\mathbf{A}_{1} f_{0}\right)^{\top}+\mathbf{A}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{V}_{1} \mathbf{A}_{1}-2 \mathbf{V}_{10} \mathbf{A}_{1}\right]^{-1}
$$

16: $\quad$ Update $\boldsymbol{f}_{0}$ :

$$
\boldsymbol{f}_{0} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{A}_{1}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{v, 1} \mathbf{A}_{1}\right)^{-1} \mathbf{A}_{1}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{v, 1} m_{1}
$$

17: Collect updated parameters as $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1} \leftarrow\left(\mathbf{P}_{1}, \mathbf{Q}_{1}, \sigma_{x, 1}^{2}, \sigma_{y, 1}^{2}, \mathbf{A}_{1}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{v, 1}, \boldsymbol{f}_{0}\right)$
18: until convergence $\left\|\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0}\right\|<\epsilon$ or $S$ iterations are reached
19: return Final estimates from $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}$

# D. 2 Missing data scenario 

An additional advantage of the probabilistic formulation of PLS is that it also allows us to directly deal with missing observations. Missing observations are the staple in most real-world scenarios as these can arise from distinct data release schedules, different collection techniques, data corruption, etc. To compare our PTFA method, we introduce an additional modification allowing us to deal with missing data.

This is a standard approach when using EM-type algorithms, as the expectation step with missing data can be easily computed by a simple imputation step based on the current EM estimate. The full procedure is presented in Algorithm 2. In our provided package, we allow all of our methods and extensions to deal with missing data using this same idea.

To test the performance of our proposed method under missing data, we generate observations for $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}$ as in the previous examples, additionally introducing a given percentage of missing-at-random observations for both. That is, we choose corruption levels $\rho_{x} \%$ and $\rho_{y} \%$ to set that fraction of elements randomly as missing. We compare two potential solutions to the missing data issue:

1. Create an imputed version of the data ( $\overline{\mathbf{X}}$ and $\overline{\mathbf{Y}}$ ) that sets the missing values in $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}$ to a fixed value, such as 0 or the sample average. We can then apply both PLS or our PTFA $\overline{\mathbf{X}}$ and $\overline{\mathbf{Y}}$.
2. On the other hand, we directly implement our PTFA with an imputation step on the inner loop of the EM algorithm based on the current predicted value for $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}$ (as proposed in Eqs. 12 and 13).

Figure D. 4 presents median $R^{2}$ statistics across 100 replications for this exercise, when we vary the level of missing-at-random observations in both features $\left(\rho_{x}\right)$ and targets $\left(\rho_{y}\right)$. The $R^{2}$ in this scenario is computed with respect to the true, infeasible values for the targets $\mathbf{Y}$ that have no missing observations. The first and second panels represent a direct comparison of applying either PLS or PTFA on the imputed data $(\overline{\mathbf{X}}$ and $\overline{\mathbf{Y}})$, while the third represents the results from including the missing values into our EM algorithm.
Note that PLS never achieves a large value for the $R^{2}$ with imputation, which is not the case for our PTFA method. However, by implementing the imputation step in the inner loop, our method is able to deal with large amounts of missing observations in the features, only breaking down with extreme amounts of missing observations close to $50 \%$.

abstract:
We develop a probabilistic variant of Partial Least Squares (PLS) we call
Probabilistic Targeted Factor Analysis (PTFA), which can be used to extract
common factors in predictors that are useful to predict a set of predetermined
target variables. Along with the technique, we provide an efficient
expectation-maximization (EM) algorithm to learn the parameters and forecast
the targets of interest. We develop a number of extensions to missing-at-random
data, stochastic volatility, factor dynamics, and mixed-frequency data for
real-time forecasting. In a simulation exercise, we show that PTFA outperforms
PLS at recovering the common underlying factors affecting both features and
target variables delivering better in-sample fit, and providing valid forecasts
under contamination such as measurement error or outliers. Finally, we provide
three applications in Economics and Finance where PTFA outperforms compared
with PLS and Principal Component Analysis (PCA) at out-of-sample forecasting.
